{:proof/updated-at "2026-03-29T20:33:34.346578544Z", :proof/falsify-completed? true, :proof/cycles [{:cycle/id "apm-a01A01-C001", :cycle/blocker-id "root", :cycle/phase :completed, :cycle/phases-completed [:observe :propose :execute :validate :classify :integrate :commit :gate-review], :cycle/phase-data {:observe {:blocker-id "root", :notes "Construct f_k >= 0 on [0,1] with limsup f_k(x) = inf for all x, but int f_k -> 0. Then adapt to R^n. Classic measure theory construction — need bumps that are tall but thin, sliding over every point infinitely often."}, :propose {:approach "Typewriter/sliding-bump construction. For each n, divide [0,1] into n equal intervals I_{n,j}. Set f_k = sqrt(n) * chi_{I_{n,j}} where k enumerates pairs (n,j). Then int f_k = sqrt(n)/n = 1/sqrt(n) -> 0, and every x lies in some I_{n,j} for each n, so limsup f_k(x) >= sqrt(n) -> inf.", :notes "The construction is a 'sliding bump' — not dominated convergence compatible. Shows pointwise divergence is consistent with integral convergence. Students often try too-uniform constructions."}, :execute {:artifacts ["proof-inline"], :notes "CONSTRUCTION on [0,1]: Enumerate pairs (n,j) with n=1,2,... and j=1,...,n as a single sequence k=1,2,... Define f_k = sqrt(n)*chi_{[(j-1)/n, j/n]}. Then: (1) int f_k = sqrt(n)*(1/n) = 1/sqrt(n) -> 0 as k->inf (since n->inf along the enumeration). (2) Fix x in [0,1]. For each n, x lies in [(j-1)/n, j/n] for some j, so f_k(x) = sqrt(n) for the corresponding k. Thus limsup f_k(x) >= sqrt(n) for all n, giving limsup = inf. ADAPTATION TO R^n: For each k, let Q_k be a cube of side length 1/k centered at a point that cycles through a dense countable set in R^n (e.g. Q^n). Set f_k = k^{n/2} * chi_{Q_k}. Then int f_k = k^{n/2} * (1/k)^n = k^{-n/2} -> 0. Every point x is within distance 1/k of some rational point for all large k, so x is in Q_k for infinitely many k, giving limsup f_k(x) = inf."}, :validate {:validation-artifacts ["construction-complete"], :notes "Construction verified: integral computation correct, limsup argument correct. R^n adaptation uses density of rationals. All conditions satisfied."}, :classify {:classification :proved, :rationale "Explicit constructions for both [0,1] and R^n cases."}, :integrate {:rationale "Illustrates failure of dominated convergence: pointwise divergence does not prevent integral convergence. Connects to Egorov theorem, convergence in measure vs pointwise convergence.", :ledger-changes []}, :commit {:saved? true}, :gate-review {:gates-passed true, :result-status :proved}}, :cycle/started-at "2026-03-29T20:34:08.204100739Z", :cycle/updated-at "2026-03-29T20:34:08.204507752Z", :cycle/result-status :proved}], :proof/ledger {"root" {:item/id "root", :item/label "Prove a01A01", :item/status :open, :item/depends-on #{}, :item/unlocks #{}, :item/evidence-type :analytical}}, :proof/active-license nil, :proof/current-mode :CONSTRUCT, :proof/problem-id "apm-a01A01", :proof/canonical {:statement "Find a sequence of real-valued nonnegative functions $\\{f_k\\}$ on\n$[0,1]$ such that $\\forall x: \\limsup f_k(x)=\\infty$ and\n$\\int_{[0,1]}f_kdx\\rightarrow 0$. Adapt this argument to the case\nwhere the domain is $\\Rn$.\n", :closure-criterion "All parts proved analytically", :statement-hash "ad3c6c20f4921c04b09ff681186102b603c22778b8ff08cc3de2f20f80a7fefb", :version-history [{:version 0, :statement "Find a sequence of real-valued nonnegative functions $\\{f_k\\}$ on\n$[0,1]$ such that $\\forall x: \\limsup f_k(x)=\\infty$ and\n$\\int_{[0,1]}f_kdx\\rightarrow 0$. Adapt this argument to the case\nwhere the domain is $\\Rn$.\n", :hash "ad3c6c20f4921c04b09ff681186102b603c22778b8ff08cc3de2f20f80a7fefb", :changed-at "2026-03-29T20:33:34.346578544Z", :reason "Initial load from APM archive"}]}, :proof/version 0, :proof/tryharder-log [], :proof/failed-routes []}